<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise label="mcqeigentrialsolution">
  <title>Trial Solutions for the Eigenvalue Method</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For a linear homogeneous constant‑coefficient system 
      <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>, what trial solution does the eigenvalue method use?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\vec{x}(t) = \vec{v} e^{\lambda t}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The method assumes a solution of the form 
          <m>\vec{v} e^{\lambda t}</m>. 
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\vec{x}(t) = \lambda t + \vec{v}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the method uses exponential solutions, not linear ones.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\vec{x}(t) = \vec{v}\,\sin(\lambda t)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>
        Not in the first step. Sinusoidal behavior only appears later when 
        eigenvalues are complex.
      </p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqeigenvalueequation">
  <title>Obtaining the Eigenvalue Equation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      After substituting <m>\vec{x}(t) = \vec{v} e^{\lambda t}</m> into 
      <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>, which equation must the constants 
      <m>\lambda</m> and <m>\vec{v}</m> satisfy?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>P\vec{v} = \lambda \vec{v}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The substitution leads directly to the eigenvalue equation.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>P\vec{v} = \vec{0}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that equation is used to find eigenvectors once <m>\lambda</m> is known.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>P = \lambda I</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. This only holds when <m>P</m> is a scalar matrix.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqcharacteristicequation">
  <title>Computing Eigenvalues</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      To find the eigenvalues of a matrix <m>P</m> in the system 
      <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>, which equation should be solved?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\det(P - \lambda I) = 0</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Eigenvalues are roots of the characteristic equation 
          <m>\det(P - \lambda I)=0</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\det(P) = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>
        No. This would test whether <m>P</m> is singular, not find eigenvalues.
      </p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>P\vec{x} = \vec{0}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>
        This computes the nullspace, not the eigenvalues.
      </p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqeigenvaluecomputationsmall">
  <title>Computing an Eigenvalue</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let 
      <m>
        P =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          3 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 5
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
      What are the eigenvalues of <m>P</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\lambda = 3,\ 5</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Diagonal matrices have eigenvalues equal to their diagonal 
          entries, consistent with solving  
          <m>\det(P - \lambda I)=0</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\lambda = 0,\ 15</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the determinant equation does not give these roots.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\lambda = 4</m> only</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. A 2×2 matrix must have two eigenvalues (including repeats).</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqcheckeigenvector">
  <title>Checking an Eigenvector</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let 
      <m>
        P =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp 2
        \end{bmatrix},
        \vec{v} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\
          0
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
      Compute <m>P\vec{v}</m> and determine the corresponding eigenvalue.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            P\vec{v} =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              2 \\
              0
            \end{bmatrix},
             \lambda = 2
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Because 
          <m>P\vec{v} = \begin{bmatrix}2 \\ 0\end{bmatrix} = 2\vec{v}</m>,  
          the eigenvalue is <m>\lambda = 2</m>.  
          This matches the equation <m>P\vec{v} = \lambda \vec{v}</m> used in 
          the eigenvalue method.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            P\vec{v} =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              1 \\
              0
            \end{bmatrix},
            \lambda = 1
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. This incorrectly multiplies the matrix and vector.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            P\vec{v} =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              1 \\
              2
            \end{bmatrix},
             \lambda = 2
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. The second component should remain zero when multiplying by this matrix.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqeigenvectordirection">
  <title>Checking Whether a Vector is an Eigenvector</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let
      <m>
        P =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          4 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 1
        \end{bmatrix},
        \vec{v} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\
          3
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
      Compute <m>P\vec{v}</m> and determine whether <m>\vec{v}</m> is an eigenvector of <m>P</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            P\vec{v} =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              4 \\
              3
            \end{bmatrix},
          </m>
          so <m>\vec{v}</m> is <em>not</em> an eigenvector.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Because <m>P\vec{v} = (4,\,3)^{T}</m> is not a scalar multiple of 
          <m>(1,\,3)^{T}</m>, <m>\vec{v}</m> is not an eigenvector.  
          Eigenvectors must satisfy <m>P\vec{v} = \lambda \vec{v}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>P\vec{v} =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            4 \\
            3
          \end{bmatrix},</m>
          so <m>\vec{v}</m> is an eigenvector with <m>\lambda = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          No. <m>(4,3)^{T}</m> is not equal to <m>4(1,3)^{T} = (4,12)^{T}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>P\vec{v} =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \\
            3
          \end{bmatrix}</m>,
          so <m>\vec{v}</m> is an eigenvector with <m>\lambda = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No—the computation of <m>P\vec{v}</m> is incorrect.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqchecksolutionform">
  <title>Verifying a Solution from an Eigenpair</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>\lambda = 3</m> is an eigenvalue of a constant matrix <m>P</m> 
      with eigenvector 
      <m>
        \vec{v} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \\
          -1
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
      Which of the following is a solution of the system 
      <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \vec{x}(t) =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              2 \\ -1
            \end{bmatrix}
            e^{3t}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Every eigenpair 
          <m>(\lambda,\vec{v})</m> yields a solution 
          <m>\vec{x}(t)=\vec{v}e^{\lambda t}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \vec{x}(t) =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              2 \\ -1
            \end{bmatrix}
            e^{t}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. This uses <m>e^{t}</m> instead of <m>e^{3t}</m>.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \vec{x}(t) =
            \begin{bmatrix}
              6 \\ -3
            \end{bmatrix}
            e^{t}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          No. Even though the vector is a scalar multiple of <m>\vec{v}</m>, 
          the exponential must be <m>e^{3t}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

  <!-- PROBLEM 1 -->
  <exercise xml:id="eigenmethod-open-1">
    <title>Deriving the Eigenvalue Equation</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider a linear homogeneous constant-coefficient system 
        <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>.  
        Starting from the trial solution <m>\vec{x}(t) = \vec{v} e^{\lambda t}</m>, 
        derive the algebraic eigenvalue equation that <m>\lambda</m> and 
        <m>\vec{v}</m> must satisfy.  
        Explain each step clearly.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        The trial solution used is 
        <m>\vec{x}(t) = \vec{v} e^{\lambda t}</m>,  
        where <m>\lambda</m> is a scalar and <m>\vec{v}</m> is a constant vector.  
        We substitute this into <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>.  
      </p>

      <p>
        First compute the derivative:
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{x}'(t) = \lambda \vec{v} e^{\lambda t}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Substitute both expressions into the differential equation:
      </p>

      <me>
        \lambda \vec{v} e^{\lambda t}
        =
        P(\vec{v} e^{\lambda t})
        =
        (P\vec{v}) e^{\lambda t}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Since <m>e^{\lambda t}</m> is never zero, canceling it yields the 
        purely algebraic condition:
      </p>

      <me>
        \lambda \vec{v} = P\vec{v}.
      </me>

      <p>
        This is exactly the eigenvalue equation.  
        It states that <m>\vec{v}</m> must be an eigenvector of <m>P</m> with 
        eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m>.  
        The section emphasizes this derivation as the foundation of the 
        eigenvalue method. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- PROBLEM 2 -->
  <exercise xml:id="eigenmethodopen2">
    <title>Verifying an Eigenvector Solution</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Let
        <m>
          P =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 3
          \end{bmatrix},
          \vec{v} =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \\
            1
          \end{bmatrix},
          \lambda = 3.
        </m>
        Verify that <m>\vec{x}(t) = \vec{v} e^{\lambda t}</m> is a solution of 
        the system <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        We must check whether <m>\vec{x}'(t) = P\vec{x}(t)</m>.  
        Start by computing <m>P\vec{v}</m>:
      </p>

      <me>
        P\vec{v}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 3
        \end{bmatrix}
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \\ 1
        \end{bmatrix}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1\cdot 2 + 2\cdot 1 \\
          0\cdot 2 + 3\cdot 1
        \end{bmatrix}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          4 \\ 3
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Compute <m>\lambda \vec{v}</m>:
      </p>

      <me>
        \lambda \vec{v}
        =
        3
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \\ 1
        \end{bmatrix}
        =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          6 \\ 3
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Since <m>P\vec{v} \neq \lambda \vec{v}</m>,  
        the vector <m>\vec{v}</m> is <em>not</em> an eigenvector of <m>P</m>,  
        and therefore <m>\vec{x}(t) = \vec{v} e^{3t}</m> is <em>not</em> a solution.
      </p>

      <p>
        This exercise illustrates a key requirement:  
        a solution of the form <m>\vec{v} e^{\lambda t}</m> exists only when  
        <m>P\vec{v} = \lambda \vec{v}</m> holds.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <!-- PROBLEM 3 -->
  <exercise xml:id="eigenmethodopen3">
    <title>Constructing a General Solution from Two Eigenpairs</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose a system <m>\vec{x}' = P\vec{x}</m> has two distinct eigenvalues
        <m>\lambda_1 = 1</m> and <m>\lambda_2 = 4</m> with corresponding eigenvectors
        <m>
          \vec{v}_1 =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \\
            0
          \end{bmatrix},
          \vec{v}_2 =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \\
            1
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </m>
        Write down the general solution to the system and briefly explain why 
        these two solutions form a fundamental set.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Since each eigenpair <m>(\lambda_i, \vec{v}_i)</m> gives a solution 
        <m>\vec{x}_i(t) = \vec{v}_i e^{\lambda_i t}</m>,  
        we have two independent solutions:
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{x}_1(t) = 
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\ 0
        \end{bmatrix}
        e^{t},
        \vec{x}_2(t) = 
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\ 1
        \end{bmatrix}
        e^{4t}.
      </me>

      <p>
        The general solution is the linear combination:
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{x}(t) =
        C_1
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\ 0
        \end{bmatrix}
        e^{t}
        +
        C_2
        \begin{bmatrix}
          1 \\ 1
        \end{bmatrix}
        e^{4t}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Because the eigenvalues <m>1</m> and <m>4</m> are distinct,  
        the corresponding eigenvectors are automatically linearly independent.  
        Hence these two solutions form a fundamental set,  
        and every solution to the system is their linear combination,  
        exactly as described in the theory.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

</exercises>






